authorlink= |coauthors= |year= 2003|publisher= Algora Publishing|location= |isbn= 0-87586-207-1| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref={{SfnRef|Bogdanov et al.|2002}} |title=All Music Guide to Rock: The Definitive Guide to Rock, Pop, and Soul |publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation/Backbeat Books |year=2002 |last1=Bogdanov |first1=Vladimir |last3=Woodstra |first3=Chris |last2=Erlewine |first2=Stephen Thomas |isbn=978-0-87930-653-3 |oclc=47823606}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sullivan|first=Steve|title=Encyclopedia of Great Popular Song Recordings|volume=1|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-810-88296-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Weller|first=Sheila|title=Girls Like Us: Carole King, Joni Mitchell, Carly Simon--And the Journey of a Generation|year=2008|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn= 978-0-743-49147-1|ref=harv}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Contraltos In Non-Classical Music}}\n[[Category:Contraltos| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of singers]]\n[[Category:Lists of women in music]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand list|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\nThe '''[[contralto]]''' singing voice has a [[vocal range]] that lies between the F below \"[[middle C]]\" (F<sub>3</sub>) to two Fs above middle C (F<sub>5</sub>) and is the [[Voice type#Contralto|lowest type of female voice]].  In the lower and upper extremes, some contralto voices can sing from two Bs below middle C (B<sub>2</sub>)<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QcZDsQZbRTM Toni Braxton's Vocal Range (Studio: Note By Note)]. YouTube. Uploaded by trentnjones (30 April 2009). Retrieved 13 December 2016.</ref> to two B{{Music|flat}}s above middle C (B{{Music|flat}}<sub>5</sub>).<ref name=McKinney>{{cite book|title= The Diagnosis and Correction of Vocal Faults|last= McKinney|first= James\n|year= 1994|publisher= Genovex Music Group|isbn=978-1-56593-940-0}}</ref>\n\nThe term ''contralto'' was developed in relation to [[Classical music|classical]] and [[opera]]tic voices, where the classification is based not merely on the singer's vocal range but also on the [[tessitura]] and [[timbre]] of the voice. For classical and operatic singers, their voice type determines the roles they will sing and is a primary method of categorization. In classical music, a \"pure\" contralto is considered the rarest type of female voice.<ref>{{cite book|title=Songs that Never Die: Being a Collection of the Most Famous Words and Melodies Enriched with Valuable Historical and Biographical Sketches of Renowned Authors and Composers|author=Buck, Dudley, ed.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KwpAAQAAMAAJ&dq|year=1892|p=23|publisher=B.F. Johnson}}</ref> In non-classical music, singers are primarily defined by their genre and their gender, not their vocal range.<ref>Axelrod, Alan, [https://books.google.com/books?id=6giucunGumUC&pg=PA68&dq=contralto+jazz&as_brr=3#v=onepage&q=contralto%20jazz&f=false ''The complete idiot's guide to jazz''], Alpha Books, 1999, pp. 68-69 ({{ISBN|0028627318}}). See also Tarasti, Eero, [https://books.google.com/books?id=kgr1xjHP2UsC ''Signs of music: a guide to musical semiotics''], Walter de Gruyter, 2002, pp. 157-178 ({{ISBN|3110172267}})</ref> When the terms ''[[soprano]]'', ''[[mezzo-soprano]]'', ''contralto'', ''[[tenor]]'', ''[[baritone]]'', and ''[[bass (voice type)|bass]]'' are used as descriptors of non-classical voices, they are applied more loosely than they would be to those of classical singers and generally refer only to the singer's perceived vocal range. Contemporarily, the informal term ''[[alto]]'' is sometimes used interchangeably with ''contralto''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/22/arts/music/avery-amereau-is-a-rarity-in-music-a-contralto.html|work=The New York Times|title=Avery Amereau Is a Rarity in Music: A Contralto|author=Oestreich, James R.|date=21 September 2016|accessdate=4 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe following is a list of singers in [[country music|country]], [[List of popular music genres|popular music]], [[jazz]], and [[musical theatre]]{{efn|For a detailed description of the differences between the operatic and musical theatre voice see Bj\u00f6rkner, Eva,  [http://www.speech.kth.se/prod/publications/files/3003.pdf ''Why so different? Aspects of voice characteristics in operatic and musical theatre singing''], [[Royal Institute of Technology|KTH]] School of Computer Science and Communication, 2006 ({{ISBN|9171785183}})}} who have been described as contraltos.\n\n==List of names==\n<!-- ADD NAMES IN ALPHABETICAL ORDER, WITH THE FIRST LETTER OF THEIR SURNAME, IF NOT, THEN EDIT OTHER VOCAL RANGE PAGES TO MATCH THIS. Do not add a singer to this list without an inline citation to a reliable source which explicitly verifies their vocal range as contralto.\n\n1) Do not add individuals to this list who do not already have an existing Wikipedia page (or a page for their musical act). \n2) When adding individuals, use the sortname function. For the sake of consistency, if the artist uses a stage moniker that includes a respective band, use the artist's real name (first, last) in the \"name\" column; their stage name may be included in the \"Associated acts.\" Any other acts, bands, or musical groups an individual is or has been part of may go here as well.\n3) Add appropriate reliable sources in the reference column when adding individuals to this list; see Wikipedia:Reliable sources for more information.\n-->\n\n[[File:Karen Carpenter.jpg|thumb|right|180px|[[Karen Carpenter]]]]\n[[File:Cher 2015.png|thumb|180px|right|[[Cher]]]]\n[[File:Patsy Cline II.jpg|thumb|right|180px|[[Patsy Cline]]]]\n[[File: Lana Del Rey @ Grammy Museum 10 13 2019 (49311023203).jpg |thumb|right|180px|[[Lana Del Rey]]]]\n[[File:Judy Garland publicity photo.jpg|thumb|right|180px|[[Judy Garland]]]]\n[[File:Lisa Gerrard1.jpg|thumb|180px|right|[[Lisa Gerrard]]]]\n[[File:Beth_Gibbons_Portishead_Coachella.jpg|thumb|180px|right|[[Beth Gibbons]]]]\n[[File:PJ Harvey.jpg|thumb|180px|right|[[PJ Harvey]]]]\n[[File:Lauryn Hill - 2014.jpg|thumb|right|