{"title_page": "Ruby (given name)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Given Name Revised\n| name = Ruby\n| image=Cut Ruby.jpg\n| imagesize=200\n| caption=The name Ruby is taken from the name of the gemstone [[ruby]].\n| pronunciation= {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|u\u02d0|b|i}} {{respell|ROO|bee}}\n| gender = female\n| meaning = \"[[ruby]]\"\n| region = \n| nickname = \n| origin = [[Latin language|Latin]]\n| related names = Reuben, Rubi\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Ruby''' is a predominantly feminine [[given name]] taken from the name of the [[gemstone]] [[ruby]]. The name of the gemstone comes from the [[Latin language|Latin]] ''ruber'', meaning ''[[red (color)|red]]''. The ruby is the [[birthstone]] for the month of July.<ref>[http://www.behindthename.com/name/ruby Behind the Name]</ref> \n\nThe name first came into wide use for girls in the late [[Victorian era]] along with other jewel names. \n\n==Popularity==\nRuby is a currently popular name in [[English language|English]]-speaking countries. It was the second most popular name given to baby girls in [[England]] and [[Wales]] in 2009, was the 24th most popular name given to baby girls born in [[Scotland]] in 2009; was the 17th most popular name for girls in [[Ireland]] in 2009; was the second most popular name for girls in [[New Zealand]] in 2009; was among [[List_of_most_popular_given_names#Female_names_5|the top five names given to girls in several]] [[Australia|Australian]] states in 2009, 2010 and 2013; and was the 108th most popular name given to baby girls born in the [[United States]] in 2009. The name was also once rarely given to boys in the United States and was ranked in the top 1,000 names given to boys born in that country between 1900 and 1940. In its masculine form, it is occasionally used as a nickname for the name [[Reuben]].<ref>[http://www.behindthename.com/top/search.php?terms=ruby Behind the Name]</ref>\n\nAuthors Pamela Redmond Satran and Linda Rosenkrantz noted in their 2007 book ''Baby Name Bible'' that Ruby is a \"vibrant\" name with a \"sassy and [[sultry]]\" image,<ref>Rosenkrantz, Linda, and Satran, Pamela Redmond (2007). ''The Baby Name Bible''. St. Martin's Griffin. {{ISBN|978-0-312-35220-2}}, p. 244</ref>\nwhile [[Laura Wattenberg]] wrote in her 2005 book ''The Baby Name Wizard: A Magical Method for Finding the Perfect Name For Your Baby'' that Ruby has the image of a woman \"kicking up her heels\" at a [[music hall]].<ref>Wattenberg, Laura (2005). ''The Baby Name Wizard: A Magical Method for Finding the Perfect Name For Your Baby''.  Broadway. {{ISBN|0-7679-1752-9}}</ref> \n\n== Notable people ==\nNotable people with the name include:\n\n* [[Ruby Bradley]] (1907\u20132002), Army nurse\n* [[Ruby Bridges]] (born 1954), American activist, first black child to attend an all-white elementary school in Louisiana in the 20th century\n* [[Ruby Dandridge]] (1900-1987), actress\n* [[Ruby Dee]] (1924\u20132014), actress\n* [[Ruby Dhalla]] (born 1974), Canadian politician\n* [[Ruby Nash Garnett]] (born 1939), lead singer of American group ''[[Ruby & the Romantics]]''\n* [[Ruby Gilbert]] (1929-2010), American politician\n* [[Ruby Goldstein]] (\"Ruby the Jewel of the Ghetto\"; 1907\u201384), American welterweight boxer and referee\n* [[Ruby Keeler]] (1910\u20131993), actress, singer and dancer\n* [[Ruby Laffoon]] (1869\u20131941), 43rd [[Governor of Kentucky]]\n* [[Ruby Lin]] (born 1976), Taiwanese actress\n* [[Ruby McKim]] (1891\u20131976), English quilt designer, entrepreneur, and writer\n* [[Ruby Modine]], American actress and singer\n* [[Ruby Murray]] (1935\u20131996), Northern Irish singer\n* [[Ruby Myers]] (1907\u20131983), also known as Sulochana, Indian silent film actress\n* [[Ruby Payne-Scott]] (1912\u20131981), pioneering Australian astronomer\n* [[Ruby Rose]] (born 1986), Australian MTV VJ\n* [[Ruby Riott]] (born 1991), ring name of American professional wrestler Dori Prange\n* [[Ruby Rubacuori]] (born 1993), Karima el Mahroug, allegedly had sex with the Italian prime minister Silvio Berlusconi when underage\n* [[Ruby (Egyptian singer)|Ruby]] (born 1981), real name Rania Hussein Muhammad Tawfiq, Egyptian singer, actress and model\n* [[Ruby Schleicher]] (born 1998), Australian rules footballer\n* [[Ruby Walsh]] (born 1979), Irish jockey\n* [[Ruby Wax]] (born 1953), comedian\n* [[Ruby Winters]] (1942\u20132016), American soul singer\n* [[Ruby Yang]], Chinese-American filmmaker\n* [[Ruby Oultram]] a famous furry, she starred in the movie 'no shame'\n===Fictional characters===\n* [[Ruby Kurosawa]], a character from the media-mix project ''Love Live! Sunshine!!''\n* [[List of RWBY characters#Ruby Rose|Ruby Rose]], the main protagonist of the animated web series ''[[RWBY]]''\n*Ruby, the main character from the [[Max & Ruby]] TV Series\n*Ruby, a character from the Cartoon Network TV series ''[[Steven Universe]]''\n*Ruby, a character from the cartoon ''[[Trollz]]''\n*Ruby, a (male) character in the ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Adventures]]'' manga series\n*Ruby, a demon character from the CW TV series ''[[Supernatural]]''\n*[[Ruby Dobbs]], a character in UK soap opera ''[[Coronation Street]]''\n*Ruby Spark, a character in UK drama ''[[Casualty (series)|Casualty]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{given name}}\n\n[[Category:English given names]]\n[[Category:Feminine given names]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Given Name Revised\n| name = Ruby\n| image=Cut Ruby.jpg\n| imagesize=200\n| caption=The name Ruby is taken from the name of the gemstone [[ruby]].\n| pronunciation= {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|u\u02d0|b|i}} {{respell|ROO|bee}}\n| gender = female\n| meaning = \"[[ruby]]\"\n| region = \n| nickname = \n| origin = [[Latin language|Latin]]\n| related names = Reuben, Rubi\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Ruby''' is a predominantly feminine [[given name]] taken from the name of the [[gemstone]] [[ruby]]. The name of the gemstone comes from the [[Latin language|Latin]] ''ruber'', meaning ''[[red (color)|red]]''. The ruby is the [[birthstone]] for the month of July.<ref>[http://www.behindthename.com/name/ruby Behind the Name]</ref> \n\nThe name first came into wide use for girls in the late [[Victorian era]] along with other jewel names. \n\n==Popularity==\nRuby is a currently popular name in [[English language|English]]-speaking countries. It was the second most popular name given to baby girls in [[England]] and [[Wales]] in 2009, was the 24th most popular name given to baby girls born in [[Scotland]] in 2009; was the 17th most popular name for girls in [[Ireland]] in 2009; was the second most popular name for girls in [[New Zealand]] in 2009; was among [[List_of_most_popular_given_names#Female_names_5|the top five names given to girls in several]] [[Australia|Australian]] states in 2009, 2010 and 2013; and was the 108th most popular name given to baby girls born in the [[United States]] in 2009. The name was also once rarely given to boys in the United States and was ranked in the top 1,000 names given to boys born in that country between 1900 and 1940. In its masculine form, it is occasionally used as a nickname for the name [[Reuben]].<ref>[http://www.behindthename.com/top/search.php?terms=ruby Behind the Name]</ref>\n\nAuthors Pamela Redmond Satran and Linda Rosenkrantz noted in their 2007 book ''Baby Name Bible'' that Ruby is a \"vibrant\" name with a \"sassy and [[sultry]]\" image,<ref>Rosenkrantz, Linda, and Satran, Pamela Redmond (2007). ''The Baby Name Bible''. St. Martin's Griffin. {{ISBN|978-0-312-35220-2}}, p. 244</ref>\nwhile [[Laura Wattenberg]] wrote in her 2005 book ''The Baby Name Wizard: A Magical Method for Finding the Perfect Name For Your Baby'' that Ruby has the image of a woman \"kicking up her heels\" at a [[music hall]].<ref>Wattenberg, Laura (2005). ''The Baby Name Wizard: A Magical Method for Finding the Perfect Name For Your Baby''.  Broadway. {{ISBN|0-7679-1752-9}}</ref> \n\n== Notable people ==\nNotable people with the name include:\n\n* [[Ruby Bradley]] (1907\u20132002), Army nurse\n* [[Ruby Bridges]] (born 1954), American activist, first black child to attend an all-white elementary school in Louisiana in the 20th century\n* [[Ruby Dandridge]] (1900-1987), actress\n* [[Ruby Dee]] (1924\u20132014), actress\n* [[Ruby Dhalla]] (born 1974), Canadian politician\n* [[Ruby Nash Garnett]] (born 1939), lead singer of American group ''[[Ruby & the Romantics]]''\n* [[Ruby Gilbert]] (1929-2010), American politician\n* [[Ruby Goldstein]] (\"Ruby the Jewel of the Ghetto\"; 1907\u201384), American welterweight boxer and referee\n* [[Ruby Keeler]] (1910\u20131993), actress, singer and dancer\n* [[Ruby Laffoon]] (1869\u20131941), 43rd [[Governor of Kentucky]]\n* [[Ruby Lin]] (born 1976), Taiwanese actress\n* [[Ruby McKim]] (1891\u20131976), English quilt designer, entrepreneur, and writer\n* [[Ruby Modine]], American actress and singer\n* [[Ruby Murray]] (1935\u20131996), Northern Irish singer\n* [[Ruby Myers]] (1907\u20131983), also known as Sulochana, Indian silent film actress\n* [[Ruby Payne-Scott]] (1912\u20131981), pioneering Australian astronomer\n* [[Ruby Rose]] (born 1986), Australian MTV VJ\n* [[Ruby Riott]] (born 1991), ring name of American professional wrestler Dori Prange\n* [[Ruby Rubacuori]] (born 1993), Karima el Mahroug, allegedly had sex with the Italian prime minister Silvio Berlusconi when underage\n* [[Ruby (Egyptian singer)|Ruby]] (born 1981), real name Rania Hussein Muhammad Tawfiq, Egyptian singer, actress and model\n* [[Ruby Schleicher]] (born 1998), Australian rules footballer\n* [[Ruby Walsh]] (born 1979), Irish jockey\n* [[Ruby Wax]] (born 1953), comedian\n* [[Ruby Winters]] (1942\u20132016), American soul singer\n* [[Ruby Yang]], Chinese-American filmmaker\n\n===Fictional characters===\n* [[Ruby Kurosawa]], a character from the media-mix project ''Love Live! Sunshine!!''\n* [[List of RWBY characters#Ruby Rose|Ruby Rose]], the main protagonist of the animated web series ''[[RWBY]]''\n*Ruby, the main character from the [[Max & Ruby]] TV Series\n*Ruby, a character from the Cartoon Network TV series ''[[Steven Universe]]''\n*Ruby, a character from the cartoon ''[[Trollz]]''\n*Ruby, a (male) character in the ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Adventures]]'' manga series\n*Ruby, a demon character from the CW TV series ''[[Supernatural]]''\n*[[Ruby Dobbs]], a character in UK soap opera ''[[Coronation Street]]''\n*Ruby Spark, a character in UK drama ''[[Casualty (series)|Casualty]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{given name}}\n\n[[Category:English given names]]\n[[Category:Feminine given names]]\n", "name_user": "Aquaduct04372", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable people", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruby_(given_name)"}
{"title_page": "List of mayors of Leeds", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n[[File:Sir Edwin Airey.jpg|thumb]]\n{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox official post\n| post                     = Lord Mayor\n| body                     = Leeds\n| insignia                 = \n| insigniasize             = 120px\n| insigniacaption          = [[Coat of arms]] of [[Leeds City Council]]\n| image                    = <!--- image of incumbent --->\n| imagesize                = <!-- Example, \"150px\" -->\n| alt                      = <!-- Optional -->\n| incumbent                = Cllr Eileen Taylor\n| acting                   = <!-- \"y\" or \"yes\" if incumbent is an acting officeholder -->\n| incumbentsince           = 2019\n| style                    = [[The Right Worshipful]]\n| status                   = [[Lord Mayor]]\n| member_of                = [[Leeds City Council]]\n| residence                = \n| termlength               = One [[municipal year]]\n| precursor                = Mayor of Leeds (1661\u20131897)\n| formation                = 12 July 1897\n| abolished                = \n| deputy                   = \n| salary                   = \n| website                  = {{url|https://www.leeds.gov.uk/your-council/councillors-and-democracy/lord-mayor|Official website}}\n}}\n[[Image:Lord Airedale Sir James Kitson.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[James Kitson, 1st Baron Airedale|Sir James Kitson, 1st Baron Airedale]], first Lord Mayor of Leeds, 1896\u201397<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fraser |first1=D. |title=A History  of  Modern Leeds |publisher=Manchester University Press, 1980  England,  UK |isbn=9780719007811 |page=384 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=4Da8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA384&lpg=PA384&dq=1896+97++Leeds++Lord++Mayor++Kitson&source=bl&ots=7h0fqKgyDn&sig=ACfU3U0y5bGwLAP5qcy9uGsxuH4cnZaYxg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi88vf84e3nAhWZyjgGHTxsDogQ6AEwC3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=1896%2097%20%20Leeds%20%20Lord%20%20Mayor%20%20Kitson&f=false |accessdate=26  February  2020 |quote=James  Kitson,  1st  Baron  Airedale    Lord  Mayor  of  Leeds  1896-97...}}</ref>]]\n[[File:1922 Robert Armitage.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Robert Armitage (politician)|Robert Armitage]], Lord Mayor of Leeds, 1904\u201305.]]\n[[File:51 William Middlebrook.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[William Middlebrook]], Lord Mayor of Leeds, 1910\u201311.]]\n[[File:Edward Allen Brotherton, 1st Baron Brotherton (bust).png|thumb|right|150px|[[Edward Brotherton, 1st Baron Brotherton]], Lord Mayor of Leeds, 1913\u201314]]\n\nThe '''Lord Mayor of Leeds''' (until 1897 known as the '''Mayor of Leeds''') is a ceremonial post held by a member of [[Leeds City Council]], elected annually by the council.\n\nBy charter from [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] in 1626, the leader of the governing body of the borough of Leeds was an alderman, the first holder being [[John Savile, 1st Baron Savile of Pontefract|Sir John Savile]].<ref name=CivicTrust>[http://www.leedscivictrust.org.uk/view.aspx?id=65 Leeds Civic Trust] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527144811/http://www.leedscivictrust.org.uk/view.aspx?id=65 |date=2011-05-27 }} Leeds Coat of Arms</ref> A second charter, in 1661 from [[Charles II of England|King Charles II]], granted the title Mayor to [[Thomas Danby (mayor)|Thomas Danby]],<ref name=CivicTrust/> after whom [[Thomas Danby College]] was named. In 1893 the borough of Leeds became a city, and in 1897 [[Queen Victoria]] conferred the title of Lord Mayor on [[James Kitson, 1st Baron Airedale|James Kitson]].\n\nThe first woman to have the post was [[Jessie Beatrice Kitson]] in 1942: she was elected following the death of Arthur Clarke shortly after his election.<ref name=JBKitson>[http://www.jessiebeatricekitson.org/lordMayor.html Leeds' first woman Lord Mayor]</ref><ref name=Drinkall>Margaret Drinkall (2013) ''The Leeds Book Of Days'': November 17th, 1942 (The History Press) {{ISBN|0752479628}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the council elected Leeds first ever black Lord Mayor, Eileen Taylor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-leeds-46894476|title=Leeds to get first black Lord Mayor|date=16 January 2019|access-date=29 August 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> After serving as a Labour member of council since 2008, she was elected unanimously by fellow councillors at the authority's annual general meeting. \n\nNotable former Mayors include [[Benjamin Gott]] (1799), [[George Goodman (MP)|Sir George Goodman]] (1836), several of the [[Lupton family]], [[Henry Rowland Marsden]] (1873) and [[Alf Cooke]] of the famous printworks (1890).\n\n==List of Lord Mayors==\nSource:<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Mayors & Aldermen of Leeds since 1626|url=http://www.leeds.gov.uk/docs/List%20of%20Lord%20Mayors.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107025631/http://www.leeds.gov.uk/docs/List%20of%20Lord%20Mayors.pdf|publisher=Leeds City Council|accessdate=1 November 2017|archivedate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* 1897: [[James Kitson, 1st Baron Airedale|James Kitson]], MP for [[Colne Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Colne Valley]], 1892\n* 1898: [[Thomas Walter Harding]]\n* 1899: John Gordon\n* 1900: Frederick W. Lawson\n* 1901: Ambrose Edmund Butler\n* 1902: John Ward<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Election of Mayors |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=11 November 1902 |page_number=12 |issue=36922| }}</ref>\n* 1903: Arthur Currer Briggs\n* 1904: [[Robert_Armitage_(politician)|Robert Armitage]], MP for [[Leeds Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Leeds Central]], 1906\n* 1905: Edwin Woodhouse\n* 1906: Joseph Hepworth\n* 1907: Wilfred Lawrence Hepton\n* 1908: Frederick James Kitson\n* 1909: William Penrose Green\n* 1910: [[William Middlebrook]], MP for [[Leeds South (UK Parliament constituency)|Leeds South]], 1908\n* 1911: William Nicholson\n* 1912: Albert Wellesley Bain\n* 1913: [[Edward Brotherton, 1st Baron Brotherton|Edward Allen Brotherton]]\n* 1914: James Edward Bedford\n* 1915: [[Lupton family|Sir Charles Lupton]]\n* 1916: Edmund George Arnold\n* 1917: Frank Gott\n* 1918: Joseph Henry\n* 1919: Thomas Beveridge Duncan\n* 1920: Albert Braithwaite\n* 1921: Willie Hodgson\n* 1922: Frank Fountain\n* 1923: [[Edwin Airey|Sir Edwin Airey]]\n* 1924: Charles Granville Gibson\n* 1925: [[John Arnott (politician)|John Arnott]]\n* 1926: [[Lupton family|Hugh Lupton]]\n* 1927: George Ratcliffe\n* 1928: [[David Blythe Foster]]\n* 1929: Nathaniel George Morrison\n* 1930: Arthur Hawkyard\n* 1931: [[Fred Simpson (politician)|Fred Brown Simpson]], MP for [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]], 1935\n* 1932: Robert Holliday Blackburn\n* 1933: Albert Edward Wilkinson\n* 1934: William Hemingway\n* 1935: Percival Tookey Leigh\n* 1936: Tom Coombs\n* 1937: [[John Badlay]]\n* 1938: Rowland Winn\n* 1939: Charles Humphrey Boyle\n* 1940: Willie Withey\n* 1941: Hyman Morris\n* 1942: Arthur Clark, <small>''died 9 November,<ref>{{cite news |title= NEW MAYOR DROPPED DEAD |author= |publisher= [[The Guardian (Charlottetown)|The Charlottetown Guardian]] |date=1942-12-03 |url= http://islandnewspapers.ca/islandora/object/guardian:19421203-007 |accessdate=2019-01-04}}</ref> replaced by''</small> [[Jessie Beatrice Kitson]]\n* 1943: Albert Hayes\n* 1944: Charles Vivian Walker\n* 1945: David Beevers\n* 1946: Sir George William Martin\n* 1947: George Brett\n* 1948: George Brett\n* 1949: Norman Douglas Vine\n* 1950: Francis Hugh O\u2019Donnell\n* 1951: Francis Eric Tetley\n* 1952: Frank Barlow Burnley\n* 1953: Donald George Cowling\n* 1954: Henry Sidman Vick\n* 1955: Sir James Croysdale\n* 1956: Thomas Austin Jessop\n* 1957: Joseph Hiley\n* 1958: Mary Pearce\n* 1959: Gertrude Annie Stevenson\n* 1960: Lillian Hammond\n* 1961: Percival Arthur Woorward\n* 1962: Harold Watson\n* 1963: Edwin Wooler\n* 1964: Lizzie Naylor\n* 1965: William R Hargreave\n* 1966: Joshua Samuel Walsh\n* 1967: Lawrence Turnbull\n* 1968: John Rafferty\n* 1969: Allan Roberts Bretherick\n* 1970: Arthur Brown\n* 1971: John Trevor V Watson\n* 1972: Albert Smith\n* 1973: Kenneth Travis Davison\n* 1974: Joan de Carteret\n* 1975: Alan Pedley\n* 1976: Ernest Howard Morris\n* 1977: William Hudson\n* 1978: Harry Booth\n* 1979: Christine Mary Thomas\n* 1980: Eric Atkinson\n* 1981: Patrick Crotty\n* 1982: Doreen Jenner\n* 1983: Martin J Dodgson\n* 1984: Douglas Ernest Gabb\n* 1985: Sydney Symmonds\n* 1986: Rose Lund\n* 1987: Doreen Wood\n* 1988: Arthur Vollans\n* 1989: Les Carter\n* 1990: Bill Kilgallon\n* 1991: Ronnie Feldman\n* 1992: Denise Atkinson\n* 1993: Keith Loudon\n* 1994: Christiana Myers\n* 1995: Peggy White\n* 1996: Malcolm Bedford\n* 1997: Linda R Middleton\n* 1998: Graham Kirkland\n* 1999: Keith Parker\n* 2000: [[Bernard Atha]]\n* 2001: David Ellis Hudson\n* 2002: Bryan North\n* 2003: Neil Taggart\n* 2004: Christopher Townsley\n* 2005: William Hyde\n* 2006: Mohammed Iqbal\n* 2007: Brian Cleasby\n* 2008: Frank Robinson\n* 2009: Judith Elliott\n* 2010: James McKenna\n* 2011: Alan Taylor\n* 2012: Ann Castle\n* 2013: Tom Murray\n* 2014: David Congreve \n* 2015: Judith Chapman\n* 2016: Gerry Harper\n* 2017: Jane Dowson\n* 2018: Graham Latty\n* 2019: Eileen Taylor\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Lord Mayors of Leeds}}\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.leeds.gov.uk/council/Pages/Lord-Mayor-of-Leeds.aspx | work=Leeds City Council | title=Lord Mayor of Leeds | accessdate=2012-09-08}} General information about current Lord Mayor\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.leeds.gov.uk/docs/List%20of%20Lord%20Mayors.pdf| format=pdf | title=Lord Mayors & Aldermen of Leeds since 1626 | work=Leeds City Council | accessdate=1 November 2017}}\n\n{{Lists of Lord Mayors in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Lists of mayors in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of mayors of places in England|Leeds]]\n[[Category:Lord Mayors of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Politics of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Local government in Leeds]]\n[[Category:Ceremonial officers in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox official post\n| post                     = Lord Mayor\n| body                     = Leeds\n| insignia                 = \n| insigniasize             = 120px\n| insigniacaption          = [[Coat of arms]] of [[Leeds City Council]]\n| image                    = <!--- image of incumbent --->\n| imagesize                = <!-- Example, \"150px\" -->\n| alt                      = <!-- Optional -->\n| incumbent                = Cllr Eileen Taylor\n| acting                   = <!-- \"y\" or \"yes\" if incumbent is an acting officeholder -->\n| incumbentsince           = 2019\n| style                    = [[The Right Worshipful]]\n| status                   = [[Lord Mayor]]\n| member_of                = [[Leeds City Council]]\n| residence                = \n| termlength               = One [[municipal year]]\n| precursor                = Mayor of Leeds (1661\u20131897)\n| formation                = 12 July 1897\n| abolished                = \n| deputy                   = \n| salary                   = \n| website                  = {{url|https://www.leeds.gov.uk/your-council/councillors-and-democracy/lord-mayor|Official website}}\n}}\n[[Image:Lord Airedale Sir James Kitson.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[James Kitson, 1st Baron Airedale|Sir James Kitson, 1st Baron Airedale]], first Lord Mayor of Leeds, 1896\u201397<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fraser |first1=D. |title=A History  of  Modern Leeds |publisher=Manchester University Press, 1980  England,  UK |isbn=9780719007811 |page=384 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=4Da8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA384&lpg=PA384&dq=1896+97++Leeds++Lord++Mayor++Kitson&source=bl&ots=7h0fqKgyDn&sig=ACfU3U0y5bGwLAP5qcy9uGsxuH4cnZaYxg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi88vf84e3nAhWZyjgGHTxsDogQ6AEwC3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=1896%2097%20%20Leeds%20%20Lord%20%20Mayor%20%20Kitson&f=false |accessdate=26  February  2020 |quote=James  Kitson,  1st  Baron  Airedale    Lord  Mayor  of  Leeds  1896-97...}}</ref>]]\n[[File:1922 Robert Armitage.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Robert Armitage (politician)|Robert Armitage]], Lord Mayor of Leeds, 1904\u201305.]]\n[[File:51 William Middlebrook.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[William Middlebrook]], Lord Mayor of Leeds, 1910\u201311.]]\n[[File:Edward Allen Brotherton, 1st Baron Brotherton (bust).png|thumb|right|150px|[[Edward Brotherton, 1st Baron Brotherton]], Lord Mayor of Leeds, 1913\u201314]]\n\nThe '''Lord Mayor of Leeds''' (until 1897 known as the '''Mayor of Leeds''') is a ceremonial post held by a member of [[Leeds City Council]], elected annually by the council.\n\nBy charter from [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] in 1626, the leader of the governing body of the borough of Leeds was an alderman, the first holder being [[John Savile, 1st Baron Savile of Pontefract|Sir John Savile]].<ref name=CivicTrust>[http://www.leedscivictrust.org.uk/view.aspx?id=65 Leeds Civic Trust] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527144811/http://www.leedscivictrust.org.uk/view.aspx?id=65 |date=2011-05-27 }} Leeds Coat of Arms</ref> A second charter, in 1661 from [[Charles II of England|King Charles II]], granted the title Mayor to [[Thomas Danby (mayor)|Thomas Danby]],<ref name=CivicTrust/> after whom [[Thomas Danby College]] was named. In 1893 the borough of Leeds became a city, and in 1897 [[Queen Victoria]] conferred the title of Lord Mayor on [[James Kitson, 1st Baron Airedale|James Kitson]].\n\nThe first woman to have the post was [[Jessie Beatrice Kitson]] in 1942: she was elected following the death of Arthur Clarke shortly after his election.<ref name=JBKitson>[http://www.jessiebeatricekitson.org/lordMayor.html Leeds' first woman Lord Mayor]</ref><ref name=Drinkall>Margaret Drinkall (2013) ''The Leeds Book Of Days'': November 17th, 1942 (The History Press) {{ISBN|0752479628}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the council elected Leeds first ever black Lord Mayor, Eileen Taylor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-leeds-46894476|title=Leeds to get first black Lord Mayor|date=16 January 2019|access-date=29 August 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> After serving as a Labour member of council since 2008, she was elected unanimously by fellow councillors at the authority's annual general meeting. \n\nNotable former Mayors include [[Benjamin Gott]] (1799), [[George Goodman (MP)|Sir George Goodman]] (1836), several of the [[Lupton family]], [[Henry Rowland Marsden]] (1873) and [[Alf Cooke]] of the famous printworks (1890).\n\n==List of Lord Mayors==\nSource:<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord Mayors & Aldermen of Leeds since 1626|url=http://www.leeds.gov.uk/docs/List%20of%20Lord%20Mayors.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107025631/http://www.leeds.gov.uk/docs/List%20of%20Lord%20Mayors.pdf|publisher=Leeds City Council|accessdate=1 November 2017|archivedate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* 1897: [[James Kitson, 1st Baron Airedale|James Kitson]], MP for [[Colne Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Colne Valley]], 1892\n* 1898: [[Thomas Walter Harding]]\n* 1899: John Gordon\n* 1900: Frederick W. Lawson\n* 1901: Ambrose Edmund Butler\n* 1902: John Ward<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Election of Mayors |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=11 November 1902 |page_number=12 |issue=36922| }}</ref>\n* 1903: Arthur Currer Briggs\n* 1904: [[Robert_Armitage_(politician)|Robert Armitage]], MP for [[Leeds Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Leeds Central]], 1906\n* 1905: Edwin Woodhouse\n* 1906: Joseph Hepworth\n* 1907: Wilfred Lawrence Hepton\n* 1908: Frederick James Kitson\n* 1909: William Penrose Green\n* 1910: [[William Middlebrook]], MP for [[Leeds South (UK Parliament constituency)|Leeds South]], 1908\n* 1911: William Nicholson\n* 1912: Albert Wellesley Bain\n* 1913: [[Edward Brotherton, 1st Baron Brotherton|Edward Allen Brotherton]]\n* 1914: James Edward Bedford\n* 1915: [[Lupton family|Sir Charles Lupton]]\n* 1916: Edmund George Arnold\n* 1917: Frank Gott\n* 1918: Joseph Henry\n* 1919: Thomas Beveridge Duncan\n* 1920: Albert Braithwaite\n* 1921: Willie Hodgson\n* 1922: Frank Fountain\n* 1923: [[Edwin Airey|Sir Edwin Airey]]\n* 1924: Charles Granville Gibson\n* 1925: [[John Arnott (politician)|John Arnott]]\n* 1926: [[Lupton family|Hugh Lupton]]\n* 1927: George Ratcliffe\n* 1928: [[David Blythe Foster]]\n* 1929: Nathaniel George Morrison\n* 1930: Arthur Hawkyard\n* 1931: [[Fred Simpson (politician)|Fred Brown Simpson]], MP for [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]], 1935\n* 1932: Robert Holliday Blackburn\n* 1933: Albert Edward Wilkinson\n* 1934: William Hemingway\n* 1935: Percival Tookey Leigh\n* 1936: Tom Coombs\n* 1937: [[John Badlay]]\n* 1938: Rowland Winn\n* 1939: Charles Humphrey Boyle\n* 1940: Willie Withey\n* 1941: Hyman Morris\n* 1942: Arthur Clark, <small>''died 9 November,<ref>{{cite news |title= NEW MAYOR DROPPED DEAD |author= |publisher= [[The Guardian (Charlottetown)|The Charlottetown Guardian]] |date=1942-12-03 |url= http://islandnewspapers.ca/islandora/object/guardian:19421203-007 |accessdate=2019-01-04}}</ref> replaced by''</small> [[Jessie Beatrice Kitson]]\n* 1943: Albert Hayes\n* 1944: Charles Vivian Walker\n* 1945: David Beevers\n* 1946: Sir George William Martin\n* 1947: George Brett\n* 1948: George Brett\n* 1949: Norman Douglas Vine\n* 1950: Francis Hugh O\u2019Donnell\n* 1951: Francis Eric Tetley\n* 1952: Frank Barlow Burnley\n* 1953: Donald George Cowling\n* 1954: Henry Sidman Vick\n* 1955: Sir James Croysdale\n* 1956: Thomas Austin Jessop\n* 1957: Joseph Hiley\n* 1958: Mary Pearce\n* 1959: Gertrude Annie Stevenson\n* 1960: Lillian Hammond\n* 1961: Percival Arthur Woorward\n* 1962: Harold Watson\n* 1963: Edwin Wooler\n* 1964: Lizzie Naylor\n* 1965: William R Hargreave\n* 1966: Joshua Samuel Walsh\n* 1967: Lawrence Turnbull\n* 1968: John Rafferty\n* 1969: Allan Roberts Bretherick\n* 1970: Arthur Brown\n* 1971: John Trevor V Watson\n* 1972: Albert Smith\n* 1973: Kenneth Travis Davison\n* 1974: Joan de Carteret\n* 1975: Alan Pedley\n* 1976: Ernest Howard Morris\n* 1977: William Hudson\n* 1978: Harry Booth\n* 1979: Christine Mary Thomas\n* 1980: Eric Atkinson\n* 1981: Patrick Crotty\n* 1982: Doreen Jenner\n* 1983: Martin J Dodgson\n* 1984: Douglas Ernest Gabb\n* 1985: Sydney Symmonds\n* 1986: Rose Lund\n* 1987: Doreen Wood\n* 1988: Arthur Vollans\n* 1989: Les Carter\n* 1990: Bill Kilgallon\n* 1991: Ronnie Feldman\n* 1992: Denise Atkinson\n* 1993: Keith Loudon\n* 1994: Christiana Myers\n* 1995: Peggy White\n* 1996: Malcolm Bedford\n* 1997: Linda R Middleton\n* 1998: Graham Kirkland\n* 1999: Keith Parker\n* 2000: [[Bernard Atha]]\n* 2001: David Ellis Hudson\n* 2002: Bryan North\n* 2003: Neil Taggart\n* 2004: Christopher Townsley\n* 2005: William Hyde\n* 2006: Mohammed Iqbal\n* 2007: Brian Cleasby\n* 2008: Frank Robinson\n* 2009: Judith Elliott\n* 2010: James McKenna\n* 2011: Alan Taylor\n* 2012: Ann Castle\n* 2013: Tom Murray\n* 2014: David Congreve \n* 2015: Judith Chapman\n* 2016: Gerry Harper\n* 2017: Jane Dowson\n* 2018: Graham Latty\n* 2019: Eileen Taylor\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Lord Mayors of Leeds}}\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.leeds.gov.uk/council/Pages/Lord-Mayor-of-Leeds.aspx | work=Leeds City Council | title=Lord Mayor of Leeds | accessdate=2012-09-08}} General information about current Lord Mayor\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.leeds.gov.uk/docs/List%20of%20Lord%20Mayors.pdf| format=pdf | title=Lord Mayors & Aldermen of Leeds since 1626 | work=Leeds City Council | accessdate=1 November 2017}}\n\n{{Lists of Lord Mayors in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Lists of mayors in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of mayors of places in England|Leeds]]\n[[Category:Lord Mayors of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Politics of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Local government in Leeds]]\n[[Category:Ceremonial officers in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Arlomaniac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added Sir Edwin Airey photo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_mayors_of_Leeds"}
{"title_page": "Danger Force", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| image                    = DangerForce.jpg\n| genre                    = \n| creator                  = Christopher J. Nowak\n| based_on                 = <!-- {{based on|work|author}} -->\n| developer                = \n| starring                 = {{plainlist |\n* Cooper Barnes\n* [[Michael Cohen (actor)|Michael D. Cohen]]\n* Havan Flores\n* Terrence Little Gardenhigh\n* Dana Heath\n* Luca Luhan\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Zack Hexum]]\n* Niki Hexum\n* Samantha Martin\n}}\n| opentheme                = \"''Danger Force'' Theme\"\n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = {{plainlist|\n* Zack Hexum\n* Niki Hexum\n}}\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1<!-- increment when new season begins -->\n| num_episodes             = 1<!-- increment when new episode airs -->\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = {{plainlist |\n* Christopher J. Nowak\n* [[Jake Farrow]]\n* Cooper Barnes\n}}\n| producer                 = {{plainlist |\n* [[Jace Norman]]\n* Andrew Hirsch\n* Andrew Thomas\n* Jessica Poter\n* Jimmy Brooks\n}}\n| cinematography           = \n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 22 minutes\n| company                  = [[Nickelodeon Productions]]\n| network                  = [[Nickelodeon]]\n| picture_format           = [[HDTV]] [[720p]]\n| audio_format             = [[5.1 surround sound]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2020|3|28}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| preceded_by              = ''[[Henry Danger]]''\n| website                  = https://www.nick.com/shows/danger-force\n| show_name                = \n}}\n\n'''''Danger Force''''' is an American television series created by Christopher J. Nowak that premiered on [[Nickelodeon]] on March 28, 2020. The series is a [[Spin-off (media)|spinoff]] of ''[[Henry Danger]]'' and includes returning stars Cooper Barnes and [[Michael Cohen (actor)|Michael D. Cohen]]. Starring alongside them are Havan Flores, Terrence Little Gardenhigh, Dana Heath, and Luca Luhan.\n\n== Premise ==\nCaptain Man and Schwoz recruit Chapa, Miles, Mika, and Bose, four new superheroes-in-training, to attend Swellview Academy for the Gifted.<ref name=\"Nickelodeon Press\" />\n\n== Cast ==\n* Cooper Barnes as Ray / Captain Man<ref name=\"Deadline Hollywood\" />, Swellview's residential superhero who is indestructible.\n* [[Michael Cohen (actor)|Michael D. Cohen]] as Schwoz<ref name=\"Deadline Hollywood\" />, Captain Man's inventor.\n* Havan Flores as Chapa<ref name=\"Nickelodeon Press\" /><ref name=\"Variety\" />, a kid who gains electrokinesis.\n* Terrence Little Gardenhigh as Miles<ref name=\"Nickelodeon Press\" /><ref name=\"Variety\" />, the brother of Mika who developed teleportation.\n* Dana Heath as Mika<ref name=\"Nickelodeon Press\" /><ref name=\"Variety\" />, the sister of Miles who develops a sonic scream.\n* Luca Luhan as Bose<ref name=\"Nickelodeon Press\" /><ref name=\"Variety\" />, the stepson of Vice-Mayor Willard who developed telekinesis.\n\n== Production ==\nOn February 19, 2020, it was announced that a ''[[Henry Danger]]'' [[Spin-off (media)|spinoff]], ''Danger Force'' will premiere on March 28, 2020. The spinoff series will see the return of Cooper Barnes as Ray / Captain Man and [[Michael Cohen (actor)|Michael D. Cohen]] as Schwoz. The series has been given a 13-episode order.<ref name=\"Deadline Hollywood\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/nickelodeon-the-astronauts-loud-house-movie-big-nate-danger-force-spongebob-slate-1202862754/|title=''The Astronauts'', Live-Action ''Loud House'' Movie, ''Big Nate'' Series, ''Henry Danger'' Spinoff on Nick's Slate|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Nellie Andreeva|date=February 19, 2020|access-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref> In addition, Havan Flores as Chapa, Terrence Little Gardenhigh as Miles, Dana Heath as Mika, and Luca Luhan as Bose are also set to star in the series. Christopher J. Nowak created the series and serves as executive producer. Cooper Barnes and [[Jace Norman]] serve as producers for the series. Omar Camacho serves as executive producer.<ref name=\"Nickelodeon Press\">{{cite press release|url=https://www.nickpress.com/press-releases/2020/02/19/nickelodeon-expands-the-world-of-henry-danger-with-all-new-danger-force-spinoff|title=Nickelodeon Expands the World of ''Henry Danger'' with All-New ''Danger Force'' Spinoff|publisher=[[Nickelodeon]]|via=Nickelodeon Press|date=February 19, 2020|access-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/nickelodeon-henry-danger-spinoff-danger-force-1203507156/|title=Nickelodeon Plans to Leap from ''Henry Danger'' to ''Danger Force''|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|author=Brian Steinberg|date=February 19, 2020|access-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNickelodeon announced on March 17, 2020 that production on all live action shows have been put on hold due to the Coronavirus.\n\n== Episodes ==\n{{Episode table\n| background      = #F46D25\n| overall         = \n| title           = \n| titleR          = <ref name=\"The Futon Critic\" /><ref name=\"Zap2it\" />\n| director        = \n| writer          = \n| airdate         = \n| airdateR        = <ref name=\"The Futon Critic\" /><ref name=\"Zap2it\" />\n| prodcode        = \n| prodcodeR       = <ref name=\"The Futon Critic\" />\n| viewers         = \n| country         = U.S.\n| episodes        = \n\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| Title           = The Danger Force Awakens\n| DirectedBy      = Mike Caron\n| WrittenBy       = Christopher J. Nowak\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|28}}\n| ProdCode        = 101\n| Viewers         = 0.89<ref name=\"1-01\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-saturday-cable-originals-network-finals-3-28-2020.html|title=Top 150 Saturday Cable Originals\u00a0& Network Finals: 3.28.2020|work=[[Showbuzz Daily]]|author=[[Mitch Metcalf]]|date=March 31, 2020|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = It has been three weeks since Captain Man and Kid Danger have defeated Drex. With Henry now operating in Dystopia, Captain Man and Schwoz open up the Swellview Academy of the Gifted where they get Chapa, Miles, Mika, and Bose as their students ever since they were exposed to the energies of the Omega Weapon. Schwoz has been teaching the kids the L.I.E. (short for Lying is Everything) to conceal their secret identity. After a comical drill, the Danger Force learns that Swellview is in the middle of a crime drought. When Captain Man is called somewhere, he claims that he is visiting to them as a way to fight crime. Later that night, Captain Man zaps the different news people to keep the Danger Force about stopping the theft of a goat who says \"but.\" The Danger Force figures out that Captain Man has been lying about the crime drought. Due to the accusations of lying, Captain Man does another cover-up as he goes to prevent a kid named Crank and his two followers from freeing their grandfather from Swellview Prison. The Danger Force teleports to Swellview Prison where they try to help fight the bad guys. Due to the Danger Force have not yet controlled their powers and Mika's powers finally manifesting, they mess up in the first battle and accidentally free the Toddler, Frankini, Goomer, the Beekeeper, Dr. Minyak, Jeff, the Time Jerker, Jack Frittleman, the Thumb Buddies, and other unnamed criminals from Swellview Prison. As the Danger Force agrees with Captain Man that they need more training, Frankini keeps going around due to the costumes that he smuggled into Swellview Prison.\n| LineColor       = F46D25\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| Title           = Say My Name\n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|4}}\n| ProdCo